	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>India looks for increased trade and economic cooperation with Africa </h1>

			
			<h4>
												05 July 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to an Indian press report, the Indian government is looking to launch a process leading to the initiation of free-trade area negotiations between India and COMESA. Senior Indian commerce ministry officials told reporters that there has been ‘a realisation that India has lost ground in Africa’ compared to China, and that Chinese trade with Africa is now double that of India. According to the report, ‘while India has independent trade ties with South Africa and Egypt, its involvement with other nations has been poor.’ India is looking to establish ‘a joint study group to explore modalities for an FTA with COMESA’, with ECOWAS being the next target for Indian trade diplomacy. The overall aim is to boost trade with Africa from US$45bn to US$75bn by 2015.</p><p>Press analysis argues that there is a distinct development dimension to India’s renewed trade engagement with Africa, with India looking for targeted collaboration linked to improving productivity and assisting movement up commodity value chains. Examples cited include collaboration with the West African cotton group to sustainably boost cotton yields, and the establishment of diamond-processing facilities in Botswana to assist Botswana in moving up the diamond value chain.</p><p>The analysis also notes the relative lack of direct Indian investment links with Africa, with ‘almost all of India’s cash’ going to Mauritius, ‘a tax haven used to route investments’ to other geographic areas.</p><p>The Indian initiative needs to be seen in the context of the Second Africa–India Forum Summit held in Addis Ababa in May 2011. Economic cooperation was given a high priority in the background document to the summit, the Africa–India framework for enhanced cooperation, and the final declaration of the summit, the Addis Ababa declaration, explicitly referred to strengthening partnerships with regional economic communities and the importance of promoting trade and investment. A US$5bn credit line is to be offered to African countries over the next three years, with a focus on support to ‘infrastructure development, regional integration and capacity building and human resources development in Africa’. To date, Indian private-sector investment has been focused on non-agricultural areas (notably oil and minerals).</p><p>In preparation for the summit, the African Development Bank (ADB) produced a briefing on ‘India’s economic engagement with Africa’, revealing a massive increase in trade in recent years (US$1bn in 1990, US$3bn in 2000, US$36bn in 2007/08, and down slightly to US$32bn in 2010/11). Oil, gold and minerals dominate African exports to India, with agro-food products playing a role in Indian exports. Investment in agribusiness development in Africa has been identified as one of five priority areas, according to the ADB analysis: ‘India’s expertise in agro-processing and small farm mechanization’ and in agribusiness development are seen as particularly relevant. Recent investments in Sierra Leone were highlighted, while a similar initiative is pending in Gambia.</p>
		
		
