				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Given recent criticism of China’s engagement with Africa, which is reproducing the traditional pattern of commodity exports (see <i>Agritrade </i>article, ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Topics/ACP-regional-trade/Africa-urged-to-diversify-and-structurally-transform" target="_blank">Africa urged to diversify and structurally transform</a>’, July 2011), the question arises of whether India’s efforts to re-energise its policy on trade with Africa can open opportunities for the development of investment and trade that will enable producers and processors in the COMESA region to move up their respective value chains, so that more value is added locally prior to export. If local value-added processing can be developed on trade with India (for example in blending and packaging teas and roasting and packaging single-origin coffee beans), then experience and economies of scale could be gained to enable value-added exports to major trading partners such as the EU.</p><p>It is unclear, given its largely free-trade area status, whether COMESA is in a position to conduct FTA negotiations on behalf of its members with countries such as India. This issue is not only related to the pooling of national sovereignty over trade negotiations with third parties, but is also linked to capacity constraints, given the complexities involved in moving forward the tripartite FTA (T-FTA) negotiations between EAC, COMESA, and SADC and the extensive time-frame envisaged (2 to 5 years) for the conduct of the detailed negotiations within this T-FTA process.</p>
		</div>
		
